<td class="mbox-text" style="">This article <b>may require <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Cleanup" title="Wikipedia:Cleanup">cleanup</a> to meet Wikipedia's <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style">quality standards</a>.</b> Please <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ising_model&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ising_model&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow">improve this article</a> if you can. <small><i>(December 2008)</i></small></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The <b>Ising model</b>, named after the physicist <a href="/wiki/Ernst_Ising" title="Ernst Ising">Ernst Ising</a>, is a <a href="/wiki/Mathematical_models_in_physics" title="Mathematical models in physics">mathematical model</a> in <a href="/wiki/Statistical_mechanics" title="Statistical mechanics">statistical mechanics</a>. It has since been used to model diverse phenomena in which bits of information, interacting in pairs, produce collective effects.</p>
